{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1vuillard_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280604574/1945082101/0402.xml":{"full_text":"Most of 30th Division\nDue in New York on\nQueen Mary Today\nBr the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK. Aug. 21\u2014Most of\nthe 30th (Old Hickory) Division\nwill arive in New York today from\nEurope aboard the Queen Mary.\nThe giant ship, carrying 14,809\ntroops, is one of four transports ar\nriving here with a total of nearly\n17,000 GI's. She is expected to dock\nat 10:15.\nOther ships arriving: Hawiian\nShipper, diverted from the Pacific,\nwith 1.813 troops; Occidental Vic\ntory, 29, and Sarah J. Hale, 2.\nThe following army units are\nscheduled to arive in East Coast\nports today:\nAt New York (Aboard Queen\nMary) elements of the 30th Infan\ntry Division, including 117th, 120th\nInfantry Regiments, divisional\nheadquarters and headquarters com\npanies of the 113th, 118th, 197th,\n230th Field Artillery Battalions;\nMilitary Police Platoon, 370th Ord\nnance Company, light maintenance.\n30th Quartermaster Company; 30th\nSignal Company; 105th Engineer\nCombat Battalion; 105th Medical\nBattalion; 30th Reconnaissance\nTroop (mechanized); 30th Counter\nIntelligence Detachment; 193d Photo\nInterpretation Team and a di\nvisional reorganization detachment.\nOther units aboard are elements\nof the 104th, 119th, 154th General\nHospitals; 2d Photo Technical\nSquadron; 434th, 435th, 436th. 437th\nMilitary Police Patrol Detachments;\nelements of the 91st, 158 th and\n188th General Hospitals.\n(Aboard Hawaiian Shipper) di\nverted from the Pacific, 707th Air\nMateriel Squadron, Headquarters\nand Base Service Squadron of the\n547th Air Service Group, 341st Sig\nnal Company, Headquarters of the\n350th Fighter Group, 345th and\n436th Fighter Squadrons, 973d Air\nEngineer Squadron, 31st Depot Sup\nply Company. 347th Fighter Squad\nron, 262d Station Hospital.\nAt Newport News, Va.\u2014(Aboard\nGeneral El ting) 165 casual troops\nand (aboard J. W. McAndrew) 1,848\ntroops diverted from the Pacific.\nFour More U. S. Divisions\nIn Europe Ready for Return\nPARIS. Aug. 21 Four more\nAmerican divisions were alerted\nyesterday for shipment home in the\nquickening redeployment of high\npoint troops eligible for discharge.\nThese were the 9th Armored of\nRemagen Rhine Bridge fame, the\n70th, 99th and 106th Infantry Divi\nsions\u2014the last one of the most\ncruelly punished outfits in the\nArdennes break-through last Decem\nber. The 35th Division is shuttling\nto the United Kingdom to board\nhomebound ships. The 137th Regi\nment will leave Le Havre on Au\ngust 23.\nThe 13th Air-borne Division is ex\npected to clear Le Havre today.\nThe 45th Division is moving to\nLe Havre and is expected to sail for\nEngland August 26.\nThe 5th, 6th and 14th Armored,\nthe 17th Air-borne and the 63d, 69th i\nand 103d Infantry Divisions previ\nously have been alerted for ship\nment home.\nie millionth troop to leave Ger-1\nmany since Germany surrendered!\nboarded ship yesterday at Le Havre.\nHe is corpl. Almon N. Conger, To\ncoma. Wash., a combat medic of the\n35th Division.\nSofia Press Prints\nByrnes' Statement\nBy the Associated Press.\nSOFIA, Bulgaria. Aug. 21\u2014Sofia\nnewspapers published without com\nment Secretary of State Byrnes\u2019\nstatement that the United States i\ndoes not consider the Bulgarian\ngovernment adequately representa\ntive of important democratic ele\nments.\nOtechestven Front, organ of the\nFatherland Front, the political co- j\nJ alition controling the government,\nj published the story beside an article\ni from the Soviet magazine Novoe j\nJ Vremje declaring that \u201cthe course\nwhich Bulgaria follows is in com-\nJ plete accord with the democratic j\nprinciples established in the Crimea j\nand at Potsdam.\u201d\nMr. Byrnes on Saturday said ar\nrangements for Bulgaria's August 26\ngeneral election do not appear free\nfrom elements of fear of force and\nintimidation. Newspapers yesterday\nsaid the withdrawal from the race\nof former ministers in an opposition\ngroup, who sought postponement of\nthe elections, failed of its objective,\n_\nMOSCOW. Aug. 21 (/P).\u2014'The Su\npreme Soviet has released Georgi\nDimitrov from Soviet citizenship\n\u2022and duties as a deputy to the Su\npreme Soviet, opening the way for\njhis campaign for a seat in the Bul\ngarian Parliament, Dimitrov, one\nJof Europe's best-known Commun\nist leaders and a former secretary\nJof the Communist International, is\npeeking election as a candidate of\n\u2022the Patriotic Front Party.\nChina\ni (Continued Prom First Page.)\n\u00abr-\u2014--\u2014\n\n\u2022upon your coming to Chungking to\ndiscuss and jointly formulate our\nRational policies,\u201d Chiang said.\n\u201cIf this request should be com\nTplied with I shall not be the only\nTone who will be benefited. For\n\u2022this reason I am sending you an\n'pther invitation and shall greatly\nappreciate your early arrival.\u201d\nt Won\u2019t Alter Surrender Plan.\nI Chiang emphasized that \"no re\ncrudescence of civil war can be tol\nera ted.\u201d\n\u201cDuring eight years of war our\nJ fellow countrymen have gone\nthrough untold sufferings,\u201d he said.\n\"Now that they are liberated they\nJ should be given consolidation and\nencouragement without delay.\u201d\nAt the same time, Chiang declared\ni he could n6t accede to the demands\nof Gen. Chu Teh, Communist army\ncommander, for participation in the\nJapanese surrender arrangements.\n-Chiang previously had ordered chu\nto take no independent action with\nregard to disarming the Japanese\ntor taking over territory the Jap\nanese now hold.\nChiang said it appeared that Chu\n\"is not fully acquainted with the\nprocedure of Japanese surrender.\u201d\n\u201cIt should be noted,\u201d he declared,\n\"that measures for accepting the\nI Japanese surrender had been de\nJ. Cided by the Allied supreme com\n\u00bbmand to be carried out separately\nthe various theaters of war, in\ncluding the China theater. There\nfore, we cannot violate what we and\nthe Allied forces have agreed\n\u00bbPoh.\nI\nBOSTON.\u2014HOSPITAL BED FOUND FOR CHILD\u2014Lt. and Mrs.\nTravis D. Bryan of Malden, Mass., with their daughter Diana, 3,\nwho was admitted yesterday to the Hospital Cottages for Chil\ndren at Baldwinsville, Mass. Arrangements for her admission\nto the institution, which specializes in treatment of crippled\nchildren, were sponsored by the Greater Boston United War\nFund Agencies. Diana, suffering from spastic paralysis, was\nbrought to public attention by newspaper stories quoting her\nparents as saying they were unable to find proper treatment\nfor he*~-_'_\u2014AP Wirephoto.\nCongress\n_(Continued From First Page.l\nmittee\u2014and a bill to reorganize the\nexecutive branch of the Govern\nment.\nTlie House Ways and Means\nCommittee will start hearings next\nweek on unemployment compensa\ntion legislation, but Chairman\nDoughton told reporters last week\nhe was doubtful if it could have\na bill in shape by September 5.\nThe House Military Affairs Com\nmittee is scheduled to meet next\nweek to consider, among other\nthings, proposals to terminate the\ndraft law before its normal expira\ntion date, next May 15. However,\nthere is some doubt whether a quo\nrum of the committee would be on\nhand.\nFavors Truman Plan.\nAs his committee prepared to take\nup the surplus property issue next\nweek, Mr. Manasco told a reporter\nhe favors President Truman\u2019s pro\nposal to give authority over the\nprogram to a single administrator\ninstead of the present three-man\nboard.\nThe committee chairman added\nthat he doubts whether more than\n$15,000,000,000 could be recovered\nfrom the estimated $100,000,000,000\nin war surpluses slated for disposal.\nLease-Lend\n<Continued From First Page.' i\ninterest of the United States to:\ncomplete them.\n\"The Foreign Economics admin-:\nistrator furthermore is instructed to!\nnegotiate with Allied governments\nfor possible procurement by them\nof lease-lend inventories now in\nstockpiles or in process of delivery.\n\u201cIf the military needs lease-lend\nsupplies for movement of troops or\nfor occupation purposes, the mili\ntary will be responsible for pro\ncurement.\u201d\nMr. Ross said that he could offer\nno further information on the ter\nmination beyond that contained in\nthe statement and said he did not\nknow what the status of reverse\nlease-lend would be in the future.\nThe termination order ends the\nflow of supplies so far as \u201cgive-away\u201d\nlease-lend is concerned. Goods or\ndered under lease-lend which some\nof these countries will continue to\nget by prior agreement, will have to\nbe taken on a credit basis.\nBut the countries without excep\ntion are short of dollars and none\ntoo strong on credit because of the\nimpact of the war on their econ\nomies.\nDepend on Export-Import Bank.\nThe official notices reecived by\nforeign economic officials yesterday\ninvited them to discuss with their\nAmerican colleagues how their post\nwar purchasing programs may be\nset up. At the moment, they may\nobtain loans only from the Export\nImport Bank, which has available\nlittle more than $3,000,000,000. In\nits last year of operation lease-lend\nfunneled more than $14,000,000,000\nof military and civilian supplies\nabroad.\nEventually foreign buyers will be\nable also to finance certain pur\nchases through the projected in\nternational bank with total credit\nresources of $9,100,000,000. But that\ninstitution probably will not be in\ncperation for a year.\nAside from the problem of trade,\nthe day of reckoning is at hand on\nlease-lend settlements between the\nUnited States and the recipient\ncountries. It is expected that goods\nexpended in the war will be written\naff as a contribution to the Allied\nvictory.\nBut there are other items of man\nufacturing equipment which will\ncontinue to be useful in the postwar\nperiod. Payment almost certainly\nwill be requested for these.\nDoolittle\nt Continued From First Page.)\nstrictly a one-way ticket.\u201d Accord\ning to recent dispatches, the threat\nwas made by the man who now\nheads the Japanese government,\nPrince Naruhiko Higashi-Kuni.\nIn the Doolittle raid, 16 twin\nengined Mitchell bombers took off\nfrom the decks of the Hornet in\nrough weather 800 miles at sea from\nTokyo. Participating in the raid\nwere 79 officers and men. They\nstruck Tokyo at noon.\nThe raid was a surprise and only\n30 Japanese planes rose to intercept.\nSome of these were shot down.\nAfter the Americans had unloaded\ntheir bombs they dived to tree-top\nlevel to avoid antiaircraft fire. Not\none of the planes reached the Chi\nnese landing fields to which they\nwere all supposed to go. The long\nflight in stormy weather drained\nthe gasoline reserves.\nA majority of the men bailed out\nand the rest crash dived. Most of\nthem landed in unoccupied China,\nbut twq plane loads went down in\nenemy-occupied territory and one\nlanded in Russia.\nDetails Secret for a Tear.\nDetails of the raid were kept se\ncret for a year. Then the War De\npartment disclosed that eight of the\nTokyo raiders had been captured by\nthe Japanese.\nThe White House statement said\nthe Government heard from enemy\nbroadcasts on October 19, 1942, of\nthe capture, trial and severe punish\nment of the Americans. On March\n12, 1943, the Government received\nthrough neutral sources confirma\ntion that the death penalty had\nbeen pronounced.\nThe eight captured flyers with the\nhome addresses of their nearest kin\nwere: Lt. George Barr, Madison, Wis.;\nLt. William Glover Farrow, son of\nMrs. Jessie S. Farrow, formerly of 1901\nBiltmore street N.W., Washington;\nLt. Robert L. Hite. Earth, Tex.; Lt.\nRobert J. Meder, Lakewood, Ohio;\nLt. Chase J. Nielson, Hyrum, Utah;\nLt. Dean E. Hallmark, Dallas, Tex.;\nCorpl. Jacob D. Deshazer, Madras,\nOreg., and Sergt. Harold A. Spatz,\nLebo, Kans.\nSurrender\n(Continued From First Page.)\n\nand his forces landed in Japan.\nThat broadcast was in English.\nArmed Forces' Surrender Only\nThe Tokyo radio told Asiatic\nlisteners\u2014in Japanese\u2014that \u201cun\nconditional surrender,\u201d in the Pots\ndam Declaration, evidently meant\nthe unconditional surrender of\nJapan\u2019s armed forces only\u2014and\nthat the Allied occupation would\ncover only \"militarily or political\nly important points.\u201d\nThat broadcast could have been\ndesigned to sooth the \"hot-headed\u201d\nmilitarists referred to in earlier\nEnglish-language broadcasts which\nhinted that there might be internal\nupheavals on occupation day. Ac\nceptance of the Allied terms, the\nEnglish-speaking announcer said,\nwas \"resented by a considerable por\ntion of the military men,\u201d and \"there\nis no telling what unfortunate in\ncidents may occur which might en\ndanger the present delicate situa\ntion.\u201d\nThe Japanese government officially\ninformed Gen. Mac Arthur it would\nbe necessary to keep Japanese armed\nforces in the homeland for the\npresent, to maintain order. The new\npremier, Gen. Prince Higashi-Kuni,\nbroadcast an appeal to the Japanese\npeople \"to maintain strict discipline.\u201d\nGen. MacArthur\u2019s headquarters\nindicated his strong air, sea and land\nforces will be ready for any emer\ngency as they near Japan.\nHeadquarters sources reported,\nhowever, that Japan\u2019s surrender\nenvoys gave every evidence of\nsincerity despite obvious distate for\ntheir task.\nJapan\u2019s protest to Gen. MacAr\nthur over \u201cthe confused situation\u201d\nin China also was bglieved sincere,\nalthough there was no headquarters\ncomment. The Japanese govern\nment said both Chinese Communist\nand Central Chinese government\ntroops were \"rushing unwarrantedly\nand without discipline\u201d into areas\nunder Japanese control, each seek\ning to be first to claim Japanese sur\nrender. The message urged Gen.\nMacArthur to send investigators to\nlearn \"the actual situation.\u201d\nIn reporting the return to Japan\nof the surrender planes, Tokyo ex\nplained that the arrival of the first\nplane was delayed by engine trouble\nwhich forced an unscheduled land\ning between Ie Island and Tokyo.\nThe second plane, which had slid\ninto a ditch as it neared the takeoff\nrunway at Ie Island, had remained\nthere overnight.\nWashington dispatches reported\nthat in addition to the four major\nPacific Allies, five other countries\u2014\nFrance, Australia, Canada, New\nZealand and the Netherlands\u2014will\nbe represented at surrender cere\nmonies. The United States, Russia,\nEngland and China will participate\ndirectly in the capitulation cere\nmony. Others will be observers.\nThe Russian Army will be repre\nsented at Gen. Mac Arthur\u2019s head\nquarters by Lt. Gen. Derevyanko,\nthe Moscow radio said last night.\nA Paris announcement said Maj.\nGen. Jacques Le Clerc was en route\nto Manila to represent France. The\nDutch news agency reported that\nLt. Gen. L. H. Van Oyen, com\nmander in chief of the Netherlands\nIndies army, would leave Melbourne\ntoday for Manila as the Netherlands\u2019\nrepresentative.\nHenry IV of France ordered the\ndeath penalty for users or importers\nof indigo.\nBloom Favors Giving\nAnother Billion to\nUNRRA (or Relief\nBy the Associated Preaa.\nHie United Nations Relief and\nRehabilitation Administration may\nreceive another $1,000,000,000 from\nthis country to head off famine\nand suffering in foreign lands.\nChairman Bloom of the House\nForeign Affairs Committee says he\nfavors turning over the money with\nno strings on its use. He will call\nhis group for hearings on the pro\nposal in three or four weeks.\nHie United States \u2018already has\nprovided $1,350,000,000 for UNRRA,\nor a little more than half of the\ntotal subscribed by nations support\ning the agency.\nMr. Bloom told newsmen yester\nday that UNRRA had made no re\nquest for the additional sum but\nthat he had reports from two For\neign Affairs Subcommittees now in\nEurope that there was a ''terrible\nsituation.\u201d Italy alone will need\nhalf a billion of aid, he estimated.\n\"At least $1,000,000,000 more is\nneeded from the United States, and\nit must be provided early this fall,\nor many war-devastated countries\nwill have a terrible winter,\u201d he as\nserted.\n\u201cWe must put up this much now\nor a lot more will be required later.\n\u201cIf we don\u2019t there's a grave danger\nhunger and pestilence will sweep\nthe world.\u201d\nUNRRA Bookkeeping Held\nGrossly Inadequate\nEy the Associated Press.\nLONDON, Aug. 21.\u2014The account\ning procedure of the United Nations\nRelief and Rehabilitation Adminis\ntration has proved grossly inadequate\nand in one case a \"compTete break\ndown in recording\u201d was threatened,\nit was disclosed at an UNRRA\nCouncil meeting yesterday.\nThe failure to establish a satis\nfactory bookkeeping system was re\nvealed in a discussion of an auditors\u2019\nreport which made clear, however,\nthat there was no charge of mis\ndirection of UNRRA funds or re\nsources.\nThe council had intended to vote\non the auditors' report yesterday,\nbut the Russian delegation ob\njected, requesting more time for\nstudy.\nLack of Personnel Blamed.\nThe auditors\u2019 report said unsatis\nfactory accounting was due to the\nlack of competent personnel, pro\ncedure, communications and trans\nportation.\nThe report blamed member gov\nernments for their unwillingness to\ncomply with UNRRA\u2019s request for\npersonnel.\nUNRRA officials said UNRRA\nDirector General Herbert H. Leh\nman already had taken some meas\nures to Improve UNRRA's financial\nadministration.\nRussia May Use Veto.\nMeanwhile, there were indica\ntions that Russia might use her\nveto power to block the addition of\nFrance, Canada. Australia, Brazil\nand Yugoslavia to the central com\nmittee of UNRRA. UNRRA\u2019s char\nter requires the vote of each mem\nber on the existing committee\ncomposed of Britain, the United\nStates, China and Russia\u2014before\nother nations can be added.\nIn the background of her position\nwas Russia\u2019s request for $700,000,000\naid, which the council has not yet\ndiscussed openly. It is believed she\nmight agree to the expansion of the\ncentral committee beyond the Big\nFour if her petition was met.\nIntentional Violators\nFace Court Action\n\u201cIntentional violators\u201d of ra\ntioning and price laws face criminal\naction instead of administrative\nsuspension of privileges to sell com\nmodities, Carl W. Berueffy, OP A\nDistrict enforcement attorney, said\ntoday.\n\"Suspension orders are no longer\ngood sanctions against intentional\nviolators now that much of the\nrationing restrictions have been\nlifted,\u201d he said.\nMr. Berueffy said that where\n\"Intentional violators\u2019\u2019 were dis\ncovered, the case would be referred\nto the United States Attorney for\ncriminal action.\nHe declared \"only current\u201d cases\nwould be examined to determine if\ncriminal action is necessary. There\nare approximately 75 to 100 cases\ncurrent, but only a small number\nwill be referred for court action, he\nadded.\n\u201cWe have no intention of going\nback into our files for the past three\nyears to punish past violators,\u201d he\nsaid, \"nor do we intend to start\ncriminal proceedings against unin\ntentional violators.\u201d\nAdministrative proceedings against\nseven restaurants were postponed by\nMunicipal Court until September 17.\n\u201cThese will be tried either as ad\nministrative or criminal cases,\u201d he\ndeclared.\nUNRRA Approves Aid\nFor Italy and Austria\nBy the Associated Pres*.\nLONDON, Aug. 21.\u2014Delegates to\nthe third UNRRA conference to\nday approved the controversial\nAmerican-backed proposal to send\naid to Italy and Austria, with the\nonly opposing vote coming from\nYugoslavia.\nRussia previously had indicated\nobjections to helping Italy and it was\nunderstood that the change in the\nSoviet position was due to a re\nported compromise in which aid\nwas assured for the Ukraine and\nWhite Russia.\nYugoslavia objected to treating\nItaly on the same basis as other\nliberated nations.\nThe American resolution appar\nently put Moscow in a delicate posi\ntion, since the Russians have been\ntrying to gain prestige and influ\nence in Italy and at the same time\nhave developed friendlier relations\nwith Yugoslavia than any other\npower. The Soviet delegation ap\nparently has been awaiting instruc\ntions from Moscow on the issue.\nNAM Says 3 Billions\nFrozen by Cancellations\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Aug. 21.\u2014The Na\ntional Association of Manufacturers\nhas estimated that about $3,000,000,\n000 in private funds will be tied up\nfor six months or more by Govern\nment cancellations of war contracts.\nThe sum will be owed to .70,000\nprime contractors and 2,000,000 sub\ncontractors employing 7,000,000,\nNAM said.\nJohn Jay was the first American\nSecretary of State.\nNLRB Certifies Union\nFor Du Pont Workers\nBy the Associated Press.\nThe National Labor Relations\nBoard has certified the United\nWorkers. Inc., to represent em\nployes of the E. I. du Pont de Ne\nmours Co. of Waynesboro, Va.,\nin matters of collective bargaining\nwith respect to pay, hours of em\nployment and other conditions of\nemployment, it was announced to\nday.\nEmployes at the Waynesboro\nplant selected the United Workers,\nInc., to be their union at an elec\ntion July 25-27.\nNewsprint Conference\nSeeks fo Restore 1941\nProduction Level\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Aug. 21\u2014A deter\nmined effort to increase the low\nsupply of newsprint through direct\ndealings between newspaper pub\nlishers and experts and the pro\nducers themselves was opened to\nday at a two-day session.\nA seven-man \u201ctask force,\u201d repre\nsenting the Newspaper Industry Ad\nvisory Committee sat down at the\nWaldorf-Astoria Hotel with repre\nsentatives of four big paper com\npanies in a continuing meeting.\nThe declared aim was to find ways\nand means of bringing newsprint\nproduction back to its 1941 level\nas quickly as possible.\nRobert Choate, publisher of the\nBoston Herald and Traveler and\nchairman of the task group, asserted\nthe paper supply situation remained\n\"serious.\u201d Too many publishers, he\nsaid, failed to realize that the war\u2019s\nend did not solve a continuing\nproblem.\nFew Early Increases Seen.\nThe consultations with producers\nhere were held privately and Mr.\nChoate said the first report of his\ngroup must be made to the News\npaper Industry Advisory Commit\ntee, which will meet on the same\nproblem with War Production Board\nofficials in Washington September\n11 and 12.\nI he task group here was faced\nwith reports, however, that few if\nany increases in newsprint supplies\nwere in immediate sight. Some in\ncreases in Canadian production are\nexpected in the last quarter of 1945\nand the first quarter of 1946. Full\nCanadian production was not pre\ndicted before the middle of next\nyear.\nScandinavian pulp production was\nnot expected to approach normal\nwithin the next 12 months and few\nof these shipments were scheduled\nto cross the Atlantic. On the con\ntrary. one authoritative report said\nsupplies of North American news\nprint probably would have to con\ntinue to be sent to Europe through\nGovernment channels for the next\nyear.\nWant Limitation Order Retained.\nIn a period when Government\ncontrols are being abandoned in\nwholesale lots, one sizable group\nof newspaper publishers is known\nto be insistent that the WPB news\nprint limitation order L-240 be re\ntained until production returns to\nits 1941 level. This same group\nargued that unless this control was\nexercised for at least another three\nto nine months a chaotic situa\ntion would result.\nAny immediate relaxation, it was\nargued, would mean a scramble for\npaper and a sharp upsweep in prices,\nwith some of the larger and more\nfavorably situated newspapers get\nting more than their share.\nMembers of the newspaper \"task\nforce\u201d in addition to Mr. Choate are\nJohn W. Potter of the Rock Island\ntill.) Argus, C. B. Short of the Roa\nnoke (Va.) Times and World News,\nErwdn Davenport of the Rochester\nIN. Y.) Times-Union and Democrat\nand Chronicle, Samuel H. Kauff\nmann of The Washington Star.\nF. M. Flynn of the New York Daily\nNews and William F. Schmick, sr.\nof the Baltimore (Md.) Sun.\nIckes Silent on Resignation\nAfter Talk With President\nCommenting that there are more\n\u2018crops\" of rumors about his inten\ntlons \u201cthan there are of alfalfa in\nMontana.\u201d Secretary of the Interior\nj Ickes today refused to discuss re\nports about his resignation after a\n30-minute conference with Presi\ndent Truman.\nAsked flatly by reporters if he had\nresigned today, Mr. Ickes said he\ncould not discuss what went on \u201cbe\ntween the President and me.\"\nMr. Truman said some time ago\nthat Mr. Ickes was going to be the\nAmerican representative to negotiate\n.\u2022n Anglo-American oil treaty, but\nthe Secretary said today no date\nhad been set for the meeting with\nthe British.\nNor did he know whether the\nprospective meeting would be held\nhere or in London, he said, telling\nreporters that \u201cwe\u2019ve offered to go\nover there if they don't care to come\nover here to enjoy our salubrious\nclimate.\"\nAs Mr. Ickes was leaving the\nWhite House he noticed a group of\nphotographers converging at the\ndoor, and remarked to the news\nmen: \u201cThey are going to take pic\ntures of the corpse.\"\nPolio Delays Opening\nOf Rockford Schools\nBy the Associated Press.\nROCKFORD, 111., Aug. 21.\u2014The\nopening of schools and start of\nhigh school football practice will\nbe delayed because of an outbreak\nof infantile paralysis that has\nstricken 154 persons and killed 17.\nThese precautions were decided\non unanimously by the school board\nlast night despite a medical opinion\nthat the peak of severity had been\npassed.\nDr. Donald W. Gudakunst of the\nNational Foundation for Infantile\nParalysis, New York, said he based\nthis opinion on the fact that none\nof the last 15 cases reported were\nthe bulbar type which afflicts the\nbase of the brain.\nft\nFort Belvoir Soldier\nDies of Polio; 3 Girls\nStricken in District\nA soldier from Fort Belvoir, Va.,\ndied Sunday at Walter Reed Hos\npital from infantile paralysis, the\nHealth Department reported today,\nbringing the deaths so far this year\nto five.\nHe was Sergt. Warren H. Shroeder,\n24, who was taken sick August 16\nand was moved to the hospital Sun\nday. His home was in Fairbury,\nNebr.\nThe soldier's case was one of four\ncases reported to the Health De\npartment today, bringing the total\nnumber of cases hospitalized in\nWashington to 108 since January 1.\nOf these, 61 were cases from the\nDistrict and 47 were non-residents\nmostly from nearby areas.\nThree Hospitalized.\nToday\u2019s cases, in addition to the\nsoldier, were two colored sisters, 5\nand 9 years of age, from the 1800\nblock of Sixth street N.W., both\nadmitted to Walter Reed, and a\n5-year-old colored girl from the\n100 block of Myrtle street N.E., sent\nto Children\u2019s Hospital.\nAlthough new cases of polio are\nbeing reported daily, Health De\npartment ofHcials today said the\noutbreak so far this year has not\nbeen as serious statistically as it\nwas last year.\nThere were 145 cases reported dur\ning the first 11 weeks\u2019 period which\nbegan in July last year, but there\nwere only 53 cases during the first\n11 weeks of the outbreak this year,\nbeginning in June.\nBelieved Now at Peak.\nThere were 12 local cases last week\ncompared with 27 during the same\nweek last year, it was added.\nDr. James G. Cumming, chief of\nthe Bureau of Preventable Diseases,\nexpressed the hope that this may\nbe the peak of the outbreak this\nseason. But all officials still shied\naway from calling the outbreak an\nepidemic.\nAsked about the use of DDT in\nRockford, 111., in a test to stem the\ntide of an epidemic there, Dr. Cum\nming questioned the experiment as\nprobably impractical.\nRichmond Passes 1944 Mark.\nFrom Richmond, Va., the Asso\nciated Press reported three new\ncases of polio yesterday, putting\nRichmond's total three above the\n1944 mark, although the \u201cseason\u201d\nfor the disease still has about a\nmonth and a half to run, according\nto health authorities. Forty-six\ncases have been reported there this\nyear, compared with 43 for 1944.\nAlthough the incidence of the\ndisease throughout Virginia is not\nconsidered alarming, Richmond\nhealth officials were concerned over\nthe high percentage reported in the\nmetropolitan area.\nTen new cases were reported\ntoday throughout Virginia by the\nl State Health Department and the\nMedical College of Virginia Hospital,\nbringing the State total for August\nto 65 and the total for the year to\n152. Last year at the close of the\nsame period, 275 cases had been\nreported in the State.\nEmployment\n_ 'Continued From First Page\nhas been in his new office only a\nfew weeks, Gen. Bradley said the\n\"greatest concern of returning vet\nerans is that of obtaining gainful\nemployment (either self-employ\njment or other) and re-establishing\nI themselves in civil life.\u201d As to the\nj bill itself, he added:\n\"The above statement is made\nwithout any desire to indicate per\nsonal approval or disapproval ol\nj the bill under consideration. Ever\nif it were appropriate to do so, I dc\nnot feel qualified to state whether\nthe bill would accomplish the pur\npose for which it is intended or\nwhether, from the political or eco\nnomic aspect, it would be desirable\nNor can I advise as to whether il\naccords with the financial program\nof the President. I merely attempl\nto state some of the very probable\neffects on veterans of any condition\nwhich would avoid depressions and\nj insure availability of work for every\none.\u201d\nPresident Truman recently called\nthe bill \u201cmust\u201d legislation and was\nrepresented as being for it again\nyesterday by Senators Wagner ol\nNew York and Murray of Montana,\nafter they conferred with him.\nVFW Spokesman Heard.\nThe committee also was told bj\nOmar B. Ketchum, national legisla\ntive representative of the Veterans\nof Foreign Wars, that the majoritj\nof returning veterans will be seek\ning new employment, \u201cand unless\nthere is full employment, they will\nbe on the bottom of all employment\nlists where seniority governs.\u201d\nMr. Ketchum explained that his\norganization has not taken a posi\ntion on the full employment bill\nsince its convention will not be\nheld until October, but he advocated\na law giving veterans seniority\ncredit, based on the length of time\nthey were in the armed forces, to\nbe used in obtaining employment.\nGen. Bradley began his brief\nstatement as follows:\n\"It is my understanding that the\n\u2022purpose of this bill is to insure full\nemployment for all persons who\nwant to work and at the same time\npreserve to the individual freedom\nof choice in the nature of his work.\nSupposedly, the effect of such legis\nlation, if enacted, would be to avoid,\nor at least level off, cycles of de\npression and inflation. Primarily\nwe are interested in avoiding post\nwar depressions, which would make\nDon\u2019t Suffer With\nAcid Condition\nMountain Valley Mineral Water, direct\nfrom famous Hot Springs. Arkansas, helps\nto correct acid condition. Mildly alkaline,\nworks naturally to help eliminate harmful\ntoxins from body. Indorsed by physicians\nfor over 75 years. Phone MI. 1062 for\nbooklet.\nMountain Valley Mineral Water\nME 1062904 12th ST. N.W.\n3\nFLIGHTS\nDAILY...\nNEW YORK TO\nTORONTO\nand across Canada\nIV. N. Y. IsM A.M.-4O0 P.M.-MI P.M.\nfOR RIMRVATIOMS all y*ur l.\u00bb| .1, ||M\n\u00ab*a a Cmadlm N.IImcI Hallways,\nm ISM. Shot, N. W\u201e Tel. NAtloal 2337\nCanada's Natlaaal Air lain, Nyine Ceest la Cnast\nand la Nawfanadlaad avar a 3,2ft mil. ravta*\ndifficult the readjustment of veter\nans to the civilian economy.\n\u201cAny condition insuring more or\nleas continuous work opportunity for\nall persons who want to be employed\nwould, in my opinion, have the fol\nlowing effect on veterans in their\nrelation to the responsibilities of the\nVeterans\u2019 Administration:\n\u201c1. Fewer veterans would apply\nor be eligible for readjustment al\nlowances (unemployment compensa\ntion).\n\"2. Fewer veterans also would ap\nply for educational benefits or\nvocational training and rehabilita\ntion. This does not imply that\nveterans in general will use these\nbenefits as a type of unemployment\ncompensation or bonus but rather\nthat, in the absence of remunerative\nemployment, undoubtedly more vet\nerans would apply for education or\ntraining benefits.\n\u201c3. Under the loan guaranty pro\nvisions of Title 111, Public 346, a\npostwar depression undoubtedly\nwould affect the ability of veterans\nto repay loans guaranteed therer\nunder. Consequently, the Govern\nment would have to make good a\ngreater amount than if full employ\nment were available and with less\nopportunity of recoupment in se\ncurity liquidation.\nClaims Indicate Depression.\n\u201c4. Many veterans with partial\ndisabilities do not claim compensa\ntion so long as gainfully employed\nExperience indicates that during a\nmajor depression claims for partial\nor even total disability benefits are\nincreased markedly.\n\u201d5. Experience also has shown\nthat the number of veterans in fa\ncilities affording domiciliary care\ndecreases with the ability to obtain\ngainful employment, and to a lesser\ndegree proportionately, this is true\nof veterans\u2019 hospital facilities.\u201d\nIn asking that Congress give vet\nerans credit for their time in uni\nform where employment in industry\nis based on seniority, Mr. Ketchum\nsaid:\n\u201cThis proposal does not advocate\n\u2018super-seniority\u2019 nor does it threaten\nunion labor or seniority regulations,\nbut it seeks an \u2018even-Stephen\u2019 break\nfor the veteran with the war worker.\nUnless statutory or implied seniority\nis granted the veterans, they will\nnot be able to penetrate the wall of\nseniority protection until all now\nwithin it are cared for. We are not\nproposing that all veterans shall\ndisplace the equivalent of non\nveterans, but we are determined\nthat if there is to be some unem\nployment, the burden should not be\nborne entirely by the returning vet\nerans, who could not accumulate\nseniority and job protection while\nin the armed forces.\u201d\nThe full employment bill is a long\nrange declaration of policy which\ncould not be put into operation in\ntime to meet the problems made im\nminent by the sudden crackup of\nJapan.\nOther Hearings Scheduled.\nOther hearings will start next\nweek in both House and Senate\ncommittees on the administration\nproposal to establish a uniform na\ntional level of unemployment com\npensation at $25 a week for a maxi\nmum period of six months during\nthe period of readjustment. Con\nsideration of this bill is expected to\nrevive the issue of State versus Fed\neral control of this phase of social\nsecurity.\nThe Senate Finance Committee\nhas notified the 48 States of its\nhearings on the question next week,\nand has received replies from 20.\nThe bill directs the President to\nThe full employment bill directs\nthe President to prepare for Con\ngress an annual budget of the ex\npenditures planned by all phases of\nprivate enterprise in the following\nyear, and an estimate of the num\nber of resulting jobs.\nIf this forecast failed to provide\nwork for the estimated total of em\nployable persons in the country,\nCongress then would consider what\nexpenditures or investments the\nFederal Government should make\nto augment the volume of private\nindustry.\n2 Soldiers Facing Death\nGet Stay of Execution\nBy the Associated Press.\nHELENA, Mont., Aug. 21.\u2014A re\nprieve through writ of habeas corpus\nstayed the execution at the Port\nMissoula disciplinary barracks of\ntwo military prisoners convicted of\ncriminal assault by a general court\nmartial in California last year, it\nj was disclosed yesterday.\nI Federal Judge Charles N. Pray\nissued the writ and ordered Col.\nA. M. Weyand, Fort Missoula com\nmandant, to stay the execution\nwhich had been scheduled August 17.\nJudge Pray ordered the prisoners\nto appear at a Federal Court hear\ning at Great Falls. September 25.\nCol. Weyand identified them as\nJohn W. Besherse, 23, of Alabama,\nand Keith E. List, 23, Logansport,\nInd.\nThe men were convicted of as\nsaulting a woman near McFarland,\nCalif., March 20, 1944. They were\ngiven the death sentence April 18,\n1944.\nDon\u2019t Cut Corns\nShed Them Off\nApply Magic-like E-Z KORN RE\nMOVER to the hardest corns and\nafter a few applications, these pain\nful corns shed off. E-Z Korn Re\nmover helps relieve com pains\u2014soft\nens dead skin, paving the way for the\nremoval of the com. Try this easy\nto-use, quick-action E-Z CORN RE\nMOVER today. 35c at (bug stores.\nNational Airport Hit\nBy Expert as Example\nOf 'What Not to Do'\nThe National Airport was labeled\nan \"excellent example of what not\nto do,\u201d in constructing landing fields\nduring a discussion of metropolitan\nairport needs at the two-day Air\nport Users\u2019 Conference, which ends\ntoday at the Statler Hotel.\nRufus Colfax Phillips, Jr., presi\ndent of Airways Engineering Con\nsultants, Inc., told the conference\nyesterday the field and terminal\nwere inadequate almost before they\nwere opened for business in June,\n1941. He pointed out that military\noperations at the field as well as\nthe Naval Air Station and Bolling\nField across the Potomac contrib\nuted largely to present congestion,\nbut he predicted peacetime commer\ncial traffic at the field alone will\nexceed the present volume of mili\ntary traffic.\nOperations Limited.\n\"Certainly some substantial in\ncreases should have been expected\nand provided for,\u201d he said.\nMr. Phillips explained the field\npermits single runways in various\nwind directions and that to install\nduel runways in compliance with\npresent instrument approach re\nquirements would necessitate either\nfurther fill-in of the river or re\nmoval of buildings and hills.\nUnder favorable weather condi\ntions, two or three operations a\nminute are now permitted &ut dur\ning instrument weather, he said,\nonly about four planes an hour can\nbe handled. This makes it neces\nsary to \u201cstack\u201d incoming planes in\nthe air, he said, and in many cases\nto send them back to their points\nof origin.\nPassengers Sent Back.\n\"It is not infrequent for a number\nof transports with a full load of\npassengers destined for Washington\non important business, to be re\nturned to Richmond, Norfolk, Balti\nmore, Pittsburgh and other places\nsimultaneously,\u201d Mr. Phillips said.\n\u201cThis certainly does not contribute\nto the future of air travel as de\npendable transportation.\u201d\nThe consultant also complained\nthat the terminal building was so\nconstructed and designed as to pro\nhibit expansion, with the result that\nticket counters had to be erected in\nthe lobby \u201cspoiling its architectural\ngrandeur, and the transport lines\nare stumbling over each other as\nbest they can.\u201d\nJulien G. Sourwine, administra\ntive assistant to Senator McCarran,\nDemocrat, of Nevada last night\ntraced the provisions of pending\nlegislation to develop a national sys\ntem of airports.\nDetails of a proposed Washing\nton Memorial Airpark will be dis\nclosed tonight by the Aero Club of\nWashington at the closing session\nof the conference.\nThe airport conference is being\nsponsored by the National Aero\nnautic Association.\nVisit\nKill Trai\u00bb'\u00bb*& 1\ngars School 1\nenJoT Jar i 1\na#l\u00a9rf\u00ab'\u00bb yea \u00ae*n. f ws, Tfitai\u00ae*- I\nc*u. whu ^arstSSSiSr 1\nO\u00bb*o 7 m Art w \"r_ I I\n[\u25a0\"ilffioTI\nI BEPMBS I\ni ej^^STlMATi\nI FRV\u00abb r-\"\u2022* 1\nI fWen on any ^jj^0 the\nd\u00a3K '^\u00a3.n.M\u00ab W\u00ab\u00bb I\nlEsss^sl\n|a\u201d\u00ab\u2014\u00bbS\nICSs.'w8\u0